Intel 8085A Microprocessor — Complete Pin-by-Pin Explanation
Chip: Intel 8085A | Package: 40-pin DIP | Technology: NMOS | Supply: +5V | Data Bus: 8-bit | Address Bus: 16-bit
The Intel 8085A is an 8-bit microprocessor introduced by Intel in 1977. It operates on a single +5V power supply and contains 6,500 transistors. The chip comes in a 40-pin Dual In-line Package (DIP). Understanding each pin is fundamental to designing 8085-based systems. The pins are numbered 1 to 40, starting from the top-left (notch side) and going counter-clockwise.




PIN 1 — X1 (Crystal / External Clock Input 1)
Pin 1 is labeled X1 and is one of two pins used to connect an external crystal oscillator to the 8085A. The crystal is connected between X1 (pin 1) and X2 (pin 2) to generate the internal clock signal required for the processor to operate. The 8085A has a built-in clock oscillator circuit; the crystal simply sets the operating frequency. Typical crystal frequencies used are 6 MHz or 6.144 MHz. The internal circuitry divides this frequency by 2, so a 6 MHz crystal produces a 3 MHz internal clock (CLK). Alternatively, an external clock source (RC network or TTL oscillator) can be connected to X1 alone, and X2 is left unconnected in that case. This pin must always be driven — the processor cannot run without a clock source.
Use: Crystal oscillator terminal 1, external clock input.

PIN 2 — X2 (Crystal / External Clock Input 2)
Pin 2 is labeled X2 and is the second crystal connection pin. When a quartz crystal is used, it is connected between X1 and X2. The crystal, along with small capacitors (typically 20–30 pF) connected from each terminal to ground, forms a stable oscillator circuit. This crystal oscillation is the heartbeat of the entire microprocessor system — it controls instruction execution timing, memory access timing, and all bus operations. If a pre-divided external clock source is applied directly to X1, pin X2 is left open (unconnected). The pair X1–X2 is critical: without them properly configured, the 8085A will not function at all.
Use: Crystal oscillator terminal 2.

PIN 3 — RESET OUT (Reset Output)
Pin 3 is the RESET OUT signal, which is an output from the 8085A. When the processor is reset (via the RESET IN pin), it drives RESET OUT HIGH to inform all peripheral devices and other chips in the system that a system-wide reset is occurring. This allows the entire system — memory chips, I/O controllers, latch ICs — to reset simultaneously along with the processor. RESET OUT remains HIGH for the duration of the reset period and goes LOW when the processor resumes normal operation. It is an active-HIGH signal. In large systems, this signal is distributed to every peripheral so that the whole system starts from a known, clean state after power-on or a manual reset.
Use: Drives external peripheral resets in synchronization with the CPU reset.

PIN 4 — SOD (Serial Output Data)
Pin 4 is the Serial Output Data pin. The 8085A includes a simple built-in serial communication facility using just two pins: SOD (output) and SID (input). The SOD pin is controlled by the SIM (Set Interrupt Mask) instruction. When the processor executes a SIM instruction with the appropriate bits set, the SOD line is driven HIGH or LOW to transmit one bit of serial data. By repeatedly executing SIM with different bit values, software can implement a basic software-driven serial communication protocol. This is a bit-banged serial port — not a hardware UART — so data rate is limited by software speed. It is commonly used for simple serial communication with terminals or other microcontrollers in older embedded systems.
Use: Software-controlled single-bit serial data output.

PIN 5 — SID (Serial Input Data)
Pin 5 is the Serial Input Data pin — the receive side of the built-in serial interface. The state of the SID pin (HIGH or LOW) is read into the processor using the RIM (Read Interrupt Mask) instruction. Bit 7 of the accumulator after a RIM instruction reflects the current logic level on the SID pin. By polling SID at timed intervals using software, the processor can receive serial data one bit at a time. Together, SOD and SID give the 8085A a minimal software-based serial communication port that requires no external UART chip. While limited in speed, this feature was very valuable in cost-sensitive designs of the late 1970s and 1980s.
Use: Software-controlled single-bit serial data input.

PIN 6 — TRAP (Non-Maskable Interrupt)
Pin 6 is the TRAP interrupt — the highest priority and non-maskable interrupt of the 8085A. Unlike other interrupts, TRAP cannot be disabled by software. No matter what the processor is doing, if TRAP goes HIGH and stays HIGH (it is both edge-triggered and level-triggered for reliability), the 8085A will immediately stop its current operation and jump to memory address 0024H to execute the interrupt service routine. TRAP is used for the most critical emergency events — power failure detection, catastrophic hardware faults, or safety-critical alarms. Its non-maskable nature ensures that even if all other interrupts are disabled, TRAP will always be serviced. This makes it essential in life-safety and power-sensitive applications.
Use: Highest priority non-maskable interrupt — used for power failure or critical hardware faults.

PIN 7 — RST 7.5 (Restart Interrupt 7.5)
Pin 7 is RST 7.5, the second-highest priority interrupt after TRAP. When this pin receives a rising edge (LOW to HIGH transition), the processor saves its current state and jumps to interrupt vector address 003CH to execute the service routine. RST 7.5 is edge-triggered, meaning it responds to the rising edge of the signal. Once triggered, it sets an internal flip-flop that remains set even if the signal goes LOW again — the interrupt is remembered and will be serviced even if brief. RST 7.5 can be masked (disabled) using the SIM instruction, allowing the programmer to selectively enable or disable it. It is commonly used for handling high-priority, time-critical external events such as a fast ADC conversion complete signal.
Use: Edge-triggered, maskable interrupt — priority level 7.5 — vector address 003CH.

PIN 8 — RST 6.5 (Restart Interrupt 6.5)
Pin 8 is RST 6.5, the third-highest priority interrupt. It is level-triggered and active-HIGH — as long as this pin is held HIGH, the interrupt request is active. The processor jumps to vector address 0034H when RST 6.5 is acknowledged. Like RST 7.5, it can be masked using the SIM instruction. Being level-triggered means it must be held HIGH until the processor acknowledges it; a brief pulse may be missed. RST 6.5 is suitable for moderately urgent external events such as a keyboard data ready signal, a timer overflow, or a communication buffer full condition. The programmer must clear the interrupt source (lower the pin) inside the ISR to prevent repeated triggering.
Use: Level-triggered, maskable interrupt — priority level 6.5 — vector address 0034H.

PIN 9 — RST 5.5 (Restart Interrupt 5.5)
Pin 9 is RST 5.5, the fourth hardware interrupt and the lowest of the three RST interrupts. It is also level-triggered and active-HIGH, directing the processor to vector address 002CH when acknowledged. RST 5.5 can be masked via the SIM instruction. It is used for lower-urgency events that can wait slightly longer than RST 6.5 or RST 7.5. Typical applications include handling a slower peripheral like a printer ready signal, a slow sensor alert, or a background communication request. All three RST interrupts (5.5, 6.5, 7.5) share the same internal interrupt enable structure and are managed together through the SIM and RIM instructions.
Use: Level-triggered, maskable interrupt — priority level 5.5 — vector address 002CH.

PIN 10 — INTR (Interrupt Request)
Pin 10 is the general-purpose INTR (Interrupt Request) pin. It is the lowest priority hardware interrupt among the five interrupt inputs of the 8085A. INTR is level-triggered and active-HIGH. When INTR goes HIGH and interrupts are enabled (via the EI instruction), the processor completes its current instruction and then acknowledges the interrupt by sending an INTA (Interrupt Acknowledge) signal. Unlike the RST interrupts, INTR does not have a fixed vector address — instead, the external hardware is expected to place a RESTART instruction (RST 0 through RST 7) on the data bus during the acknowledge cycle. This makes INTR very flexible, as the vector address depends entirely on what the external circuit provides. It is used with external interrupt controllers like the 8259A.
Use: General maskable interrupt request — lowest priority hardware interrupt — flexible vector via data bus.

PIN 11 — INTA (Interrupt Acknowledge) — Active LOW
Pin 11 is the INTA (Interrupt Acknowledge) output, and it is active LOW. When the processor has accepted an INTR interrupt request and is ready to receive the interrupt vector, it pulses INTA LOW. This signal is sent to the external device (or interrupt controller) that asserted INTR, telling it to place the appropriate RST instruction code on the data bus. The processor then reads this instruction, determines the jump address, saves the program counter on the stack, and jumps to the interrupt service routine. INTA is essentially the handshake signal in the interrupt acknowledge cycle — without it, the external hardware would not know when to present its vector code.
Use: Active-LOW output — signals external hardware to place interrupt vector on data bus.

PIN 12 — AD0 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 0)
Pin 12 is the first pin of the multiplexed Address/Data bus. The 8085A uses a technique called address/data multiplexing to reduce pin count. During the first clock cycle (T1) of any memory or I/O operation, pins AD0–AD7 carry the lower 8 bits of the 16-bit address (A0–A7). This address must be latched externally by a transparent latch IC (such as the 74LS373 or Intel 8212) using the ALE signal. After T1, during T2 and T3, the same pins switch to carrying 8-bit data (D0–D7) — either data being written to memory/IO or data being read from it. AD0 is the least significant bit of both the address and data. This multiplexing saves 8 physical pins but requires external latches to demultiplex the address from the data.
Use: Lower address bus bit A0 during T1; Data bus bit D0 during T2/T3. Bidirectional.

PIN 13 — AD1 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 1)
Pin 13 is AD1 — identical in function to AD0 but carries bit 1. During T1, it outputs address bit A1; during T2/T3 it acts as data bus bit D1. Every memory and I/O access uses all 8 AD pins (AD0–AD7) simultaneously to transfer the lower address byte and then the data byte in sequential clock cycles. The external latch captures the address on the falling edge of ALE and holds it stable for the remainder of the bus cycle, while the AD pins are free to carry data.
Use: Address bit A1 during T1; Data bit D1 during T2/T3. Bidirectional.

PIN 14 — AD2 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 2)
Pin 14 is AD2, carrying address bit A2 during the address phase and data bit D2 during the data phase. Along with AD0–AD7, this pin forms the lower half of the 16-bit address bus. The multiplexed bus design was a deliberate design choice by Intel to keep the 8085A within a standard 40-pin DIP package while still supporting a full 16-bit address space (64KB of addressable memory).
Use: Address bit A2 / Data bit D2. Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 15 — AD3 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 3)
Pin 15 is AD3, the fourth bit of the multiplexed address/data bus. It carries A3 during address time and D3 during data time. This pin, like all AD pins, is bidirectional — it can both send (output) and receive (input) signals depending on the direction of the current bus operation (read or write).
Use: Address bit A3 / Data bit D3. Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 16 — AD4 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 4)
Pin 16 carries A4 during the address phase and D4 during the data transfer phase. As part of the 8-bit data bus, D4 plays a role in every single memory read, memory write, I/O read, and I/O write operation the 8085A performs. The data transferred on D4 can represent program instructions being fetched, operand data being read, or results being written to memory or peripherals.
Use: Address bit A4 / Data bit D4. Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 17 — AD5 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 5)
Pin 17 is AD5, carrying A5 and D5 in their respective time slots. Like the other AD pins, it requires the ALE signal to be used with an external latch to separate the address from the data. In a typical 8085 system, one latch IC (like 74LS373) is dedicated to capturing AD0–AD7 when ALE is HIGH, providing a stable A0–A7 address output for the rest of the memory cycle.
Use: Address bit A5 / Data bit D5. Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 18 — AD6 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 6)
Pin 18 is AD6, the seventh bit of the lower address/data bus. It outputs address bit A6 during T1 and then serves as data bit D6 during the rest of the bus cycle. D6 is the second-most significant bit of the data byte, and for instruction opcodes, it can be significant in determining the type of operation (MOV, ADD, etc.) the processor must execute.
Use: Address bit A6 / Data bit D6. Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 19 — AD7 (Address/Data Bus, Bit 7)
Pin 19 is AD7 — the most significant bit of both the lower address byte and the data bus. A7 completes the lower 8 bits of the 16-bit address, and D7 is the most significant data bit (the sign bit in signed arithmetic). After the latch captures A0–A7, the full 16-bit address is available by combining the latched A0–A7 with the direct A8–A15 signals on pins 21–28.
Use: Address bit A7 / Data bit D7 (MSB). Bidirectional multiplexed.

PIN 20 — VSS (Ground)
Pin 20 is VSS, the ground pin of the 8085A. It is connected to 0V (GND) in the circuit. This is the reference voltage for all logic levels on the chip. All signals on the 8085A are interpreted relative to VSS. A stable, clean ground connection is critical — any noise or impedance on the ground line will corrupt data, cause spurious interrupts, and generally make the system unreliable. In PCB design, VSS is connected to a solid ground plane to minimize noise. Decoupling capacitors (typically 0.1 µF ceramic) are placed between VCC and VSS as close to the chip as possible to filter out high-frequency noise on the power supply.
Use: Ground (0V) reference for the chip. Must be connected to system ground.

PIN 21 — A8 (Address Bus, Bit 8)
Pin 21 is A8, the first of the upper 8 address bits. Unlike the lower 8 address bits (AD0–AD7), the upper address bits A8–A15 are not multiplexed — they remain stable throughout the entire bus cycle and are always dedicated to carrying address information only. A8 is therefore directly connected to the address bus of the system without needing any external latch. This simplifies the upper address decoding logic in the system design. A8 contributes to selecting which of the 256 pages (each 256 bytes) in the 64KB address space is being accessed.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 8. Output only.

PIN 22 — A9 (Address Bus, Bit 9)
Pin 22 is A9, the second upper address bit. Like A8, it is always an output and remains valid for the entire duration of the bus cycle. A8–A15 together form the “page address” in a 256-byte page memory organization. External address decoders use these 8 bits to select which memory chip or I/O device is being addressed, while A0–A7 select the specific byte within that device.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 9. Output only.

PIN 23 — A10 (Address Bus, Bit 10)
Pin 23 is A10. Together with A8, A9, A11–A15, these pins drive the chip select logic of the memory system. Since these lines are permanently dedicated to address output (no data multiplexing), they can drive chip enable inputs of memory ICs directly through address decoders (like 74LS138 or 74LS139) without any timing concerns about when the address is valid.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 10. Output only.

PIN 24 — A11 (Address Bus, Bit 11)
Pin 24 is A11. With 16 total address bits (A0–A15), the 8085A can address 2^16 = 65,536 unique memory locations (64KB). A11 is the twelfth bit in this address, and along with A12–A15, it is used to select large blocks of memory. For instance, if A15–A12 decode to a specific combination, an entire 4KB block of memory is selected. Chip designers use A11–A15 heavily for memory bank selection.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 11. Output only.

PIN 25 — A12 (Address Bus, Bit 12)
Pin 25 is A12. This pin, along with A13–A15, forms the uppermost bits of the address and is used for high-level memory and I/O space partitioning. In a typical 8085 system with ROM at the bottom of the address space and RAM at the top, A15 or A12–A15 are decoded to select the appropriate memory device. A12 represents a 4096-byte boundary in the memory map.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 12. Output only.

PIN 26 — A13 (Address Bus, Bit 13)
Pin 26 is A13. Each increment of A13 from 0 to 1 shifts the address by 8192 bytes (8KB). System designers use A13–A15 to divide the 64KB memory map into large sections — for example, the lower 32KB for ROM and the upper 32KB for RAM. A13 plays a role in all such coarse address decoding decisions.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 13. Output only.

PIN 27 — A14 (Address Bus, Bit 14)
Pin 27 is A14. With A14 = 0, the lower 16KB of any memory map can be accessed; with A14 = 1, the upper 16KB within any 32KB region is selected. Address lines A14 and A15 are especially important for the highest-level memory map partitioning in 8085 systems.
Use: Non-multiplexed upper address bit 14. Output only.

PIN 28 — A15 (Address Bus, Bit 15)
Pin 28 is A15 — the most significant address bit. A15 divides the entire 64KB address space into two equal halves: lower 32KB (A15 = 0) and upper 32KB (A15 = 1). It is the most commonly used bit in chip select logic. For example, in a simple system, A15 = 0 selects ROM and A15 = 1 selects RAM. A15 is a pure output and is always valid throughout the bus cycle.
Use: Most significant address bit — Non-multiplexed. Output only. Critical for memory bank selection.

PIN 29 — S0 (Bus Status Bit 0)
Pin 29 is S0, one of two status output pins (S0 and S1) that indicate the type of machine cycle currently being executed by the processor. Together with S1 (pin 38) and IO/M (pin 34), the S0 and S1 signals encode four possible bus states: Halt (S1=0, S0=0), Write (S1=0, S0=1), Read (S1=1, S0=0), and Fetch/Opcode Read (S1=1, S0=1). These status signals are used by DMA controllers, bus arbiters, and advanced peripheral controllers to monitor what the CPU is doing on the bus at any instant. In simpler systems, S0 and S1 may not be connected to anything, but in multi-processor or DMA-capable systems they are essential for bus management.
Use: Bus cycle status bit 0 — output signal indicating current bus cycle type.

PIN 30 — ALE (Address Latch Enable)
Pin 30 is ALE — Address Latch Enable — one of the most important control signals in the 8085 system. At the beginning of every machine cycle (during T1), ALE goes HIGH for one clock period. This HIGH pulse on ALE is used to tell the external address latch (74LS373 or similar) to capture the lower 8 address bits currently present on the AD0–AD7 pins. When ALE falls LOW, the latch enters hold mode — freezing the captured address and holding it stable for the rest of the bus cycle while the AD lines switch to carrying data. Without ALE and an external latch, the system cannot separate address from data on the multiplexed bus, and memory/IO operations would be impossible.
Use: Triggers external address latch to capture A0–A7 from the multiplexed AD0–AD7 lines.

PIN 31 — WR (Write) — Active LOW
Pin 31 is the WR (Write) signal — an active-LOW output. When the processor wants to write data to memory or an I/O port, it pulls WR LOW during the data transfer phase (T2/T3). This LOW signal is used as the write enable input to memory chips (RAM) or I/O latches — it triggers them to accept and store the data currently on the data bus (AD0–AD7). WR is HIGH during read operations and during idle states. It is combined with the IO/M signal to distinguish between memory writes and I/O writes: if IO/M is LOW and WR is LOW, it is a memory write; if IO/M is HIGH and WR is LOW, it is an I/O write.
Use: Active-LOW output — signals memory or I/O devices to latch incoming data from the data bus.

PIN 32 — RD (Read) — Active LOW
Pin 32 is the RD (Read) signal — an active-LOW output. When the processor wants to read data from memory or from an I/O port, it pulls RD LOW. This enables the addressed memory chip or I/O device to drive the data bus with its stored data. The processor then reads this data from the AD0–AD7 pins. RD goes LOW during T2 and remains LOW until the data is latched by the processor at the end of T3. Combined with IO/M: if IO/M is LOW and RD is LOW, it is a memory read; if IO/M is HIGH and RD is LOW, it is an I/O read (input from a port).
Use: Active-LOW output — enables memory or I/O device to put data onto the data bus for the CPU to read.

PIN 33 — S1 (Bus Status Bit 1)
Pin 33 is S1, the second bus status signal (working alongside S0 on pin 29). S1 and S0 together encode the current bus cycle status. S1 is HIGH during all read and opcode-fetch cycles and LOW during write cycles and halt states. External bus controllers, DMA controllers, and system monitors use S1 and S0 in combination with IO/M to precisely determine what kind of bus transaction is in progress. This information is critical in systems where multiple devices share the same bus and need to know when to assert data, when to release the bus, and when the CPU is in a special state.
Use: Bus cycle status bit 1 — output signal used with S0 to indicate current machine cycle type.

PIN 34 — IO/M (I/O or Memory Select) — Active LOW for Memory
Pin 34 is the IO/M signal — a crucial output that distinguishes whether the current bus operation is accessing memory or an I/O device. When IO/M is LOW, the address on the address bus refers to a memory location, and WR or RD controls whether data is written to or read from RAM/ROM. When IO/M is HIGH, the address on the bus refers to an I/O port number (only the lower 8 bits, A0–A7, are valid for I/O port addresses in the 8085), and WR/RD controls I/O port write/read operations. All memory chips have their chip-enable inputs driven by decoded signals that include IO/M to ensure they only activate during memory cycles, not I/O cycles.
Use: HIGH = I/O operation; LOW = Memory operation. Critical for separating memory and I/O address spaces.

PIN 35 — READY
Pin 35 is the READY input pin. This pin is used by slow memory chips or slow I/O devices to tell the processor to wait before completing a read or write operation. Normally READY is held HIGH, meaning the addressed device is ready for data transfer. If a slow device cannot respond within the standard number of clock cycles, it pulls READY LOW. The processor detects this and automatically inserts one or more WAIT states (extra T-wait clock cycles) into the current bus cycle, extending the operation until READY goes HIGH again. This allows the 8085A to interface with memory chips of any speed — from very fast SRAM to very slow EPROM — without any data errors.
Use: Input from slow devices — LOW inserts wait states to extend bus cycle timing.

PIN 36 — RESET IN (Reset Input) — Active LOW
Pin 36 is the RESET IN pin — an active-LOW input. When this pin is pulled LOW (held at 0V), the 8085A immediately resets. The program counter is cleared to 0000H, all interrupt flags are cleared, and the processor begins fetching and executing instructions from memory address 0000H (where the reset/boot program must reside). RESET IN must be held LOW for at least three clock cycles to guarantee a proper reset. On power-up, a simple RC circuit (resistor to VCC and capacitor to GND) is typically used on this pin to generate an automatic power-on reset pulse, ensuring the processor starts cleanly every time power is applied. A manual reset pushbutton is also usually connected here.
Use: Active-LOW input — resets the CPU, clears PC to 0000H, initiates boot from address 0000H.

PIN 37 — HLDA (Hold Acknowledge) — Output
Pin 37 is HLDA — Hold Acknowledge — an output from the 8085A. When an external device (such as a DMA controller like the Intel 8237) requests control of the system buses by asserting the HOLD input (pin 39), the processor responds after completing its current bus cycle by asserting HLDA HIGH. HLDA HIGH signals the DMA controller that the processor has released the address bus, data bus, and control bus. The DMA controller then takes over the buses to perform high-speed direct memory-to-memory or device-to-memory data transfers without CPU involvement. When the DMA operation is complete, HOLD is released and HLDA goes LOW, returning bus control to the processor.
Use: Output — confirms to DMA controller that CPU has released the system buses.

PIN 38 — HOLD (Hold Request Input)
Pin 38 is the HOLD input pin. An external device — typically a DMA controller — asserts HOLD HIGH when it needs to take direct control of the system buses (address, data, and control) to perform a DMA (Direct Memory Access) transfer. Upon receiving HOLD HIGH, the 8085A completes its current machine cycle, tri-states (disconnects) its address bus, data bus, and control outputs, and then asserts HLDA (pin 37) to acknowledge that the buses are now free. The processor stays in this suspended state, consuming time but not driving any buses, until HOLD is released. DMA transfers are used for fast bulk data movement (e.g., from a disk controller to RAM) that would be too slow if done one byte at a time under CPU control.
Use: Input — DMA controller requests bus control by asserting HIGH; CPU suspends and releases buses.

PIN 39 — INTR / INTA (Interrupt / Interrupt Acknowledge)
Note: Pin 39 on many 8085A diagrams is the dedicated INTA line (some references list it separately from pin 11). In the standard 40-pin mapping, pin 39 is associated with INTR combined acknowledge functions depending on the specific pinout revision. In the most widely taught configuration: this pin works in conjunction with the INTR (pin 10) and INTA (pin 11) mechanism described above. Always verify against the specific 8085A datasheet variant being used in your design. The general function relates to the interrupt bus control interaction.
Use: Interrupt-related control — see INTR (pin 10) and INTA (pin 11) descriptions above.

PIN 40 — VCC (Power Supply)
Pin 40 is VCC, the positive power supply pin of the 8085A. It must be connected to a stable, regulated +5V DC supply. The 8085A consumes approximately 170mA of current (typical) at 5V. The quality of the VCC supply directly affects the reliability of the entire system. Voltage ripple, noise spikes, or a voltage outside the 4.75V–5.25V tolerance range can cause unpredictable behavior, data corruption, or permanent chip damage. A 0.1 µF ceramic decoupling capacitor must be placed between VCC (pin 40) and VSS (pin 20) as close to the chip as physically possible on the PCB to filter out high-frequency switching noise. This is a mandatory good practice in all digital circuit designs.
Use: +5V regulated power supply input. Must be clean and stable. Always decouple with 0.1 µF capacitor to GND.
